Macedonians in referendum on changing country name
In Sunday's referendum, Macedonians voted to change the country's name to "the Republic of Northern Macedonia". The name change would resolve a decades-long dispute with Greece that has prevented the country's efforts to become a member of the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, believes that the name of the North Neighbor is in practice a regional requirement for its territory and has therefore opposed its entry into the EU and NATO.
In June, the governments of the two countries signed an agreement on a new name proposal, but nationalist opponents believe that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic majority of Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov has announced that he will not vote in a referendum, and the campaign against the vote raises doubts as to whether voter turnout will reach the required 50% limit to make the result legal.
The question on the ballot was: "Are you on the side of NATO and EU membership, accepting the agreement with Greece".
Supporters of name change such as Prime Minister Zoran Zaev reason that the price is worth paying so that Macedonia, which has emerged from the collapse of Yugoslavia, can seek both EU and NATO membership.
"I came today to vote for the future of our country, for the young people of Macedonia, so that they could live in freedom as members of the European Union, because it means a safer life for all of us," said Olivera Georgievska in Skopje, 79.
Although the vote is not legally binding, enough Members of Parliament have said they respect the outcome of the vote to have a decisive effect.
A change of name requires a two-thirds majority in Parliament.
According to the Central Election Commission, no irregularities had been reported by 1:00 p.m.
However, voter turnout was only 16, compared to 34% of the previous 2016 parliamentary elections, when 66% of those entitled to vote eventually cast their votes.
"I came to vote for my children and our place in Europe," said 62-year-old Gjose Tanevsky, who voted in the capital Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko voted in a referendum on Macedonia's name change in Strumica, Macedonia on 30 September 2018. The name change would open the way for NATO and EU membership .
Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, prepared a small stage and placed chairs in front of tents boycotting the referendum in front of the Skopje parliament.
"We support NATO and the EU, but we want to join our heads up, not through the kitchen door," Kavadarkov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they do not want to take us as Macedonia, we can turn elsewhere, like China and Russia as part of Euro-Asian integration."
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring much-needed investment in Macedonia, with an unemployment rate of over 20%.
"I believe the vast majority will vote for a name change because more than 80% of our citizens support the EU and NATO," Zaev said after giving his vote.
He said the "yes" sound was "our repulsive future."
An opinion poll published Monday by the Macedonian Political Research Institute referred to a 30-43% voter turnout in a referendum - that is, below the required activity.
In another survey commissioned by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57% of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
70% of them said they would vote for the yes option.
For a referendum to be successful, voter turnout must exceed 50% by one vote.
The failure of the referendum would be the first serious setback for a pro-Western government after it came to power in May last year.
