"Sea belongs to us": landlocked Bolivia tries to regain contact with the Pacific Ocean by legal process
Sailors patrol outside the naval base in La Paz.
A sea blue flag is flying in the flag bars of public buildings.
Navy bases from Titicaca to Amazon have been smeared with the slogan: "Justly, the sea belongs to us.
Getting it back is our duty."
In Bolivia, which remained inland, the memory of the coastline lost in Chile in the bloody 19th century resource war remains strong — as is the longing to sail in the Pacific Ocean once more.
Hope is at its highest in decades as Bolivia awaits the International Court of Justice's decision on October 1 after five years of reflection.
"Bolivia has a strong sense of progress, a spirit of community and serenity, and of course a positive attitude in waiting for a final solution," said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzad.
Several Bolivians across the country are hopeful to follow the International Court of Justice's decision on big screens, hoping that the Hague will advocate — at the end of a decades of intermittent debate — Bolivia's position that Chile has a duty to grant Bolivia independent access to the sea.
Bolivian charismatic president Evo Morales, who faces a controversial battle for re-election next year, will have a lot at stake in next Monday's policy.
"The return to the Pacific Ocean is very close," he said in late August.
Some analysts, however, believe that the court is unlikely to decide in Bolivia's interest, and even if it did, the situation would not change much.
The UN institution of Dutch origin has no competence to extradite Chilean administrative territories, and the ICJ has announced that it will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The fact that the ICJ's decision is given just six months after the last statements have been made suggests that the case "is not complicated," says Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
In addition, the last four years have slowed down rather than promoted Bolivia's intentions.
"The current Bolivian regime has hijacked the question of maritime connection," said Zárate.
The rhetoric that challenges Morales' quarrel has suppressed the rest of the Chilean benevolence, he said.
Bolivia and Chile will continue the discussions at some point, but it will be very difficult to organise negotiations after that.
Neither country has had another embassy since 1962.
Former President and Bolivian representative in The Hague, Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, does not accept the view that the court's decision was exceptionally rapid.
Monday gives Bolivia "an exceptional opportunity to start a new era in relations with Chile" and the opportunity to "end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzad also denies that Morales, one of Latin America's most popular presidents, had used the maritime issue as political support.
"Bolivia will never give up her right to connect with the Pacific Ocean," he added.
"The decision is an opportunity to understand that it is time for us to move forward from the past."
