John Edward: Language skills are a key skill for a global citizen
The learning outcomes of private schools in Scotland have traditionally been good, and this success has continued in 2018 as a result of good test results. Success has been enhanced by individual and community success in sports, art, music and other communal projects.
These schools of over 30,000 students, represented by the Scottish Private Schools Council SCIS, are located across Scotland, seeking to provide a high level of service to their students as well as to the parents of students.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for their chosen career, graduate and higher education, and global citizenship.
As an educational actor who can design and implement customized study content, we have noticed the status of languages as a popular and desirable subject to continuing in educational institutions.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a person in a language he understands, the message goes to his head.
If you speak to a person in his own language, the message goes to his heart."
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely on English only if we want to establish relationships with people from other countries.
From this year's latest test results, we find that languages are at the top of the lists in terms of access percentage among private schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved the highest grade of A.
The data were collected from 74 SCIS schools. Based on the data, it was found that 72 per cent of students who received the best grade A, 72 per cent studied Mandarin Chinese, 72 per cent studied German, 69 per cent studied French, and 63 per cent studied Spanish.
This shows that private schools in Scotland support learning foreign languages as an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are currently optional subjects, but are held in the same value as natural science subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics), both in the private school study program as elsewhere.
A 2014 survey commissioned by the UK Employment Office found that 17% of situations where the employer had difficulty finding a suitable employee for the job were explained by lack of language skills.
Language skills development is therefore even more necessary for promoting career development for young people.
The more possible tasks require language skills, the more essential these skills become in the global world.
If a person has studied another language, he or she will have the advantage of this lifelong skill in the future, regardless of the career he or she has chosen.
The ability to communicate directly with a foreigner automatically puts a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 survey commissioned by YouGov, 75% of more than 4,000 British adults are unable to have a conversation in a foreign language, and French was the only language known by a double-digit figure of 15%.
This is why investing in teaching languages is important for children today.
In particular, the knowledge of languages in developing countries gives children a better opportunity to find a meaningful career.
Within Scotland, schools differ in the languages they teach.
Several schools focus on traditional languages, while some teach specifically languages that are supposedly important to British in 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Despite your child's interests, private schools always have several language options taught by specialized teachers.
Scottish private schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future holds.
In this time, it cannot be denied that in an international business environment languages will continue to be of great importance to the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be seen as "international communication skills".
Private schools will continue to offer this freedom of choice, diversity and high-level Scottish youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the head of the SCIS Council of Private Schools in Scotland
