North Korea 'nothing' disarms itself without trust
North Korean Foreign Minister told the UN on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions only increased distrust of the United States, and under these circumstances there is no chance that North Korea would unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho said at the UN General Assembly that North Korea has taken "significant benevolent measures" in the past year, such as stopped nuclear and missile testing, dismantled the nuclear test site, and promised that North Korea will not increase the number of nuclear weapons or technology.
"However, we have not seen a similar gesture from the United States," he said.
"Without confidence in the United States, we cannot be sure that national security will remain, so under such circumstances, it is not possible to disarm ourselves unilaterally."
Although Ri reiterated the familiar lament that Washington does not accept a step-by-step nuclear weapons waiver, which would reward North Korea for every intermediate subject, his statement is nevertheless significant in the sense that unilateral disarmament was not completely excluded, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first US sitting president and North Korean leader summit in Singapore on 12 June in a statement, Kim assured of "the removal of the Korean peninsula from nuclear weapons" and Trump promised to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea has sought to officially end the Korean War of 1950-1953, but the United States has insisted that Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed the facilitation of strict international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The United States is calling for 'nuclear disarmament first', and have increased pressure through sanctions to achieve their goals by force — even against the 'declaration of peace'," Ri said.
"The notion that sanctions would bring us to our knees is the hope of indifferents.
But the problem is that the constant sanctions only deepen our distrust."
Ri did not mention plans to hold the next Kim-Trump summit, which Trump himself stressed to the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings with South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding, "If the party requiring disarmament were South Korea and not the United States, the situation would not have reached such a dead end."
Yet Ri's tone of voice was significantly different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that directing missiles towards the continental regions of the United States was inevitable after Trump called Kim a "missile man" with suicidal intentions.
Last year, Trump threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, but this year Trump praised Kim with a lot of courage to approach the abandonment of arms, but still stressed that there is still much work left and sanctions must remain until North Korea abandons nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump mentioned that he has no time deadline: "If it takes two years, three years, or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia suggested that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the progress already made.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that "the strengthening of the Security Council's sanctions must continue to be strong and unsuccessful until we prove a full, final and confirmed nuclear waiver."
The Security Council has unanimously stepped up sanctions against North Korea since 2006, with the aim of stopping the funding channels for Pyongyang ballistic and nuclear missile production.
Pompeo met with North Korea in conjunction with the UN General Assembly, and announced that he would visit Pyongyang again next month for preparations for the second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but the latest visit did not go smoothly.
When he left Pyongyang, he described the progress made, but North Korea condemned Pompeo's "gangster-like demands" just a few hours later.
North Korea committed to closing the missile base and the nuclear facility at a meeting with Secretary General Moon earlier this month in the event of the United States taking "equivalent measures".
Pompeo said Kim meant by "equivalent measures" the security guarantees Trump committed to at the Singapore meeting and moving towards normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students complete a course for adequate rest
All undergraduate students at Harvard University will attend a course this year to increase student rest. The course is a counterattack to the university's thriving macho culture, where students weigh a long night with caffeine.
According to the researcher, students from the best university in the world are often quite unaware of the basics of their own well-being.
Charles Czeisler, a professor at Harvard University School of Medicine, who works on sleep research at Brigham and Women's Hospital, believes the course is the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler got the idea for the course after lecturing on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"After the lecture, a young woman came to me and said, 'Why am I only hearing about it now, in my last year of study?'
No one had ever told him about the need for a dream, which I found surprising," he said in an interview with the Telegraph.
The course, which was held for the first time this year, guides students on how the right sleep habits support academic and athletic performance and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor at Harvard University School of Medicine and deputy director of health services at the University, says the university ended up organizing the course after they heard how students suffered severe sleep deprivation during the week of study.
The one-hour course includes a set of interactive tasks.
One section presents students with a picture of a dorm room where the student can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports equipment, and books, thus getting information about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of sleep deprivation on sports performance and the importance of regular evening activities.
The second section tells participants how long a sleep deprivation can raise the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
"We know this has no immediate impact on student behavior.
However, we believe they have the right to know about these issues in exactly the same way as they have a right to know about the health effects of smoking," says Professor Czeisler.
According to Professor Czeisler, all-night study marathons are still a matter of pride, and modern technology and the ever-increasing pressures of students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
"Getting adequate and quality sleep should be students' 'secret weapon' against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even against weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes a state similar to starvation in the brain, which is why a person is constantly hungry," the professor points out.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemical and physical psychology in California, helped Professor Czeisler plan the course after attending one of the courses he taught in his first year at Harvard last year.
He says that the course opened his eyes and gave the impetus to organizing a course covering all students on campus.
He hopes that all postgraduate students could complete a similar study module before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends students setting an alarm clock to also remind students of bedtime in addition to waking up the morning, and urges them to keep in mind the adverse effects of electrical display devices and LED lighting on the circadian rhythm, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
