Rogers: "It's a geiger meter, used to find radioactive minerals such as uranium.
When you place your headphones in your ears, you can actually hear the effect of radioactive radiation in minerals."
Evans: "Look, it's really ratting!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945 a few days before his 63rd birthday.
An invention that still bears his name is still alive.
New cancer vaccine capable of teaching the immune system to ‘see' the malignant cells
A new cancer vaccine is capable of teaching the immune system to ‘see’ the malignant cells and destroy them
Vaccine teaches the immune system to identify malignant cells as part of treatment
In the method, resistant cells are isolated from the patient and modified in the laboratory
After treatment, cells injected back into the body are able to ‘see' proteins typical of several cancers
Koerokote has given promising results in patients with various cancers.
For example, cancer cells in a patient with ovarian cancer disappeared within 18 months after being treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to identify malignant cells.
In the method, resistant cells are isolated from the patient and modified in the laboratory to be able to ‘see' the HER2 proteins typical of several cancers.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, USA, describes the method: "From our results, it is a very promising vaccine."
HER2 "directs the growth of several types of cancer," Professor Berzofsky explains. "These include breast cancer and ovarian, lung and colon cancers."
A similar approach — taking resistant cells from a patient and teaching them to attack cancer cells — has also produced results in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
